<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAWYER VIEWS REMAP CASE AS ONLY 1ST STEP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BOYARSKY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To attorney Richard P. Fajardo, the Los Angeles County redistricting case 
involves much more than putting a Latino on the Board of Supervisors for the 
first time in this century. 
</P>
<P>
Fajardo, who represents the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund 
in a Voting Rights Act suit against the county, said victory for his side will 
spur Latino political organization throughout California. 
</P>
<P>
"What I think we're going to do with the suit is to open opportunities here," 
Fajardo said during an interview in the MALDEF office in downtown Los Angeles. 
Near him were 10 volumes, each with a red cover, containing the transcript of 
the landmark trial in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Federal District Judge David V. Kenyon ruled in June that the county had 
violated the Voting Rights Act by discriminating against Latinos in the drawing 
of the five supervisorial districts in 1981. In August, Kenyon threw out a 
newly proposed county plan, saying it contained "nonsensical distortion," and 
he accepted a district alignment proposed by MALDEF. 
</P>
<P>
But that was just the first phase of the case, and Fajardo has a lot of work 
ahead of him. An appellate court is reviewing Kenyon's decision, which means 
more courtroom work for Fajardo and the other lawyers in the case. The 
plaintiffs also include the U.S. Justice Department and the American Civil 
Liberties Union. The case could go to the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
As Fajardo sees it, MALDEF's involvement in the suit is part of the 
organization's nationwide effort to put Latinos in elected office. In Texas, 
where MALDEF was involved in similar litigation, there are now 6,000 Latino 
elected officials, twice as many as in California. 
</P>
<P>
Latinos make up a third of Los Angeles County's population, but no Latino has 
served on the powerful board since 1875. A Latino Los Angeles County 
supervisor, Fajardo said, would stimulate voting registration and applications 
for citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
"Politicians will persuade people to become citizens so they can build a 
(political) base," he said. And, he said, in the high-visibility job of Los 
Angeles County supervisor, a Latino would be in a good position to run for 
statewide office. 
</P>
<P>
Finally, he said, the lawsuit will alert politicians that MALDEF will not stand 
for discrimination against Latinos when the Legislature and cities and counties 
around the state reapportion districts next year. 
</P>
<P>
In regard to Los Angeles County, he said, political leaders will begin to talk 
"about health problems in East Los Angeles . . . the alternatives to closing 
clinics. And you'll see more Latino businessmen dealing with the county." 
</P>
<P>
Those are among the reasons for MALDEF's intensity in pursuing the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
That is why it resisted demands by the supervisors that the suit be dropped and 
that both sides wait for completion of the 1990 U.S. Census to draw up new 
districts. Why push the suit, county attorneys argued, when the census will 
produce new population figures? 
</P>
<P>
And MALDEF rejected the point made by Supervisors Mike Antonovich and Deane 
Dana that the fact that Latina Sarah Flores finished first in June's primary 
election for the 1st District shows that the boundaries drawn by the 
supervisors do not discriminate against Latinos. 
</P>
<P>
Fajardo said the decision by Antonovich and Dana to back Flores was an attempt 
by the two conservatives to maintain power by trying to persuade the court that 
her strong showing proved the county was not guilty of a Voting Rights Act 
violation. 
</P>
<P>
"The board looks on Flores as a way to derail the lawsuit," Fajardo said. "It's 
classic." 
</P>
<P>
He said: "If Sarah Flores wants to run, fine, but in a Hispanic district. . . . 
If these Republicans really believe the Hispanic community is Republican, or 
about to become Republican, they shouldn't be afraid to put her up in that 
district and test her ideas." 
</P>
<P>
For Fajardo, his work on the suit is part of a commitment to helping his 
community that began when he was a student at Garfield High School and was 
turned toward activism by the East Los Angeles school walkouts in 1968 to 
protest inadequate education. "I didn't participate," he said, "but it had a 
great impact on me." 
</P>
<P>
Fajardo's grandparents left Mexico for East Los Angeles in the 1920s. Like 
thousand of other Mexican families, they were fleeing from the turmoil that 
accompanied years of revolution in their country. 
</P>
<P>
His father was born in East Los Angeles. He worked for the post office and, 
later, as a food stamp program inspector for the U.S. Department of 
Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
"Dad had a great impact on me," said Fajardo, 38. "He said I had to graduate 
from high school, and he encouraged me to go to college." 
</P>
<P>
First sign-ups for college-preparatory courses are in the eighth grade. But on 
sign-up day, the counselor handed Fajardo a program with classes such as wood 
shop, plastics and physical education. 
</P>
<P>
"I took it to my dad," Fajardo said. "He said, 'I thought you wanted to go to 
college.' I said, 'I did, but this is what they gave me.' He went down and 
talked to the counselor. The counselor said there was not enough room in the 
college-prep courses, and she wasn't sure I could compete in them." But his 
father insisted, and Fajardo was put on the college track. 
</P>
<P>
After he graduated from Garfield in 1969, Fajardo attended East Los Angeles 
College for a year and then, with the help of grants and loans, went to UC 
Santa Barbara. He got a master's degree in economics and got an internship in 
the Oxnard city treasurer's office. 
</P>
<P>
"I got into politics there," he said. "A friend and I were having trouble 
getting into the upper levels at the office," Fajardo said. "He ran for city 
treasurer and won." 
</P>
<P>
After helping with that campaign, Fajardo enrolled at UCLA Law School and, 
after graduation, clerked for a federal judge. In 1983 he joined the MALDEF 
legal staff in Washington, and three years later he was transferred to Los 
Angeles. Fajardo lives with his father in the house in which he was raised, 
near Ruben Salazar Park. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a great honor to be asked (to join the staff) by MALDEF," Fajardo said. 
"I never thought I would get it. The big firms give you a lot of work, but you 
have to work into the big cases. At MALDEF, you have a tremendous amount of 
responsibility early on." 
</P>
<P>
Fajardo was the lead lawyer against the county in the redistricting suit. 
Colleague Mark Rosenbaum, attorney for the ACLU, said Fajardo brought to the 
case experience he had gained in pursuing a similar suit against the Los 
Angeles City Council. That suit was settled, with the council agreeing to 
create a new Latino district. 
</P>
<P>
That experience helped him in questioning Latino politicians and in working 
with UCLA professor Leobardo Estrada in drawing up the redistricting plan 
eventually accepted by Kenyon. 
</P>
<P>
Rosenbaum and others who watched the trial said Fajardo brought humanity to the 
often dusty issue of redistricting. 
</P>
<P>
His own feelings came out in closing arguments. Replying to the county's 
contention that discrimination was long past, Fajardo said discriminatory 
practices had left their mark on every Latino family here. He told how his 
uncle had returned from World War II as a decorated combat veteran. 
Celebrating, he and the family went to a movie and took a center seat. Latinos 
and blacks were consigned to the balcony and the sides of theaters in those 
days, and Fajardo's uncle was asked to move. 
</P>
<P>
Fajardo recalled for the court how his uncle said, " 'If I'm not good enough to 
sit where I want, I'll just leave.' It so moved several of the Hispanic and 
black patrons that they got up and walked out." 
</P>
<P>
"It showed," Fajardo said, "that it doesn't matter how much money you have, 
your position or whether you've risked your life in the war. You can still be 
subject to the indignity of an insult based on your race or ethnicity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, MALDEF's Richard Fajardo is the lead attorney for plaintiffs in 
redistricting case. ; Photo, COLOR, Richard Fajardo with transcripts of 
redistricting court case. ROSEMARY KAUL / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
