<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: POINT MUGU; 
</P>
<P>
300 MORE SEABEES DEPLOYED TO MIDEAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRSTEN LEE SWARTZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 300 Seabees flew from Point Mugu Wednesday morning to join 350 other 
county-based personnel now in Saudi Arabia. Another 900 men based in Port 
Hueneme are expected to join troops in the Middle East within the next month, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The Seabees are a uniformed force of civil engineers and construction 
tradesmen. 
</P>
<P>
Yesterday's 11 a.m. flight completed the deployment of 650 men from Naval 
Mobile Construction Battalion 5, which started Aug. 26. 
</P>
<P>
Two other battalions based in Port Hueneme have orders to support Operation 
Desert Shield, said Kassie Gale, a spokeswoman for the Seabees. 
</P>
<P>
About 100 men of Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 4, now deployed in Puerto 
Rico, have flown to Saudi Arabia. And Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 40, 
now in Guam, will also be redeployed. 
</P>
<P>
"The only thing holding them back at this point is the availability of 
aircraft," Gale said. 
</P>
<P>
The fourth battalion based in Port Hueneme has not yet received orders to 
depart for Saudi Arabia, Gale said. 
</P>
<P>
On Sept. 6, a cargo ship left Port Hueneme with 200 pieces of heavy 
construction equipment for the Seabees. Other equipment has been deployed from 
Guam, Gale said. KIRSTEN LEE SWARTZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
