<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Carved Images Find Niches at Museum: When Spanish missionaries in the 
Philippines hired first Chinese craftsmen and then Filipinos to create images 
of the saints, ivory from elephant graveyards or the cropped tusks of working 
elephants seemed like the best material available. About 100 of the finely 
crafted works dating from 1590 to 1810 will be on display until Jan. 6 in 
"Images of Faith: Religious Ivory Carvings from the Philippines" at the Pacific 
Asia Museum in Pasadena. Clockwise from right, Barbara Still of Los Angeles 
checks detail of crucifix; the head and hands of Santa Rosa date to the 18th 
Century or before, and a display case holds 19th-Century images. LOU MACK / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
