<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOGAN LEADS FIELD IN STANTON COUNCIL CAMPAIGN FUNDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
STANTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After spending more than $1,000 on his City Council campaign, candidate Rand 
Hogan still has more cash on hand than most of his opponents have in total 
contributions, according to campaign contribution statements. 
</P>
<P>
Hogan has received $2,954 in contributions, including $999 from his wife, 
Leslie P. Hogan, and $687 in copying and related services from his employer, 
Boise Cascade Office Products in Rancho Dominguez. 
</P>
<P>
To date, Hogan has spent $1,062 and has $1,205 cash on hand. 
</P>
<P>
Candidate Harry Dotson has raised $1,878 and spent $1,027. His largest single 
contributor was his wife, Natalie G. Dotson, who provided $490. He has also 
received $1,188 in contributions of less than $100. 
</P>
<P>
The three remaining candidates have each received less than $1,100 in 
contributions, the documents show. 
</P>
<P>
Joe V. Harris has raised $1,017 and spent $815. He loaned himself $1,000 for 
the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Mayor Edward L. Allen has filed a statement saying that he will not 
spend more than $1,000 on his campaign. And candidate Don Martinez's campaign 
is powered solely by a $500 loan to himself, although he has spent no money 
yet. 
</P>
<P>
The candidates are seeking to fill three council seats in the Nov. 6 election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
